With this, we can see that several pieces of data are giving our model an unfair advantage with a strong positive and negative correlation, so lets drop these columns for our testing.

In [59]:

               'communication_method_dance', 'honeycomb_structure_hexagonal',
               'communication_method_pheromones','species_numeric'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Split for training and testing¶

In [65]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
In [66]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split( x, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state=24, )
In [67]:
X_train.shape, X_test.shape, y_train.shape, y_test.shape
Out[67]:
((8000, 45), (2000, 45), (8000,), (2000,))

Because getting rid of null values would make our data uneven, lets impute our training and testing data.

In [68]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
In [69]:
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
In [70]:
imputed_train = imputer.fit_transform(X_train)
In [71]:
imputed_test = imputer.fit_transform(X_test)

Creating our model with Random Forest¶

In [72]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
In [73]:
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 100, random_state = 42)
In [74]:
clf = clf.fit(imputed_train, y_train)
In [75]:
predicted = clf.predict(imputed_test)
